   v38.42.0: Fixes the bug where releasing items in React showed blank release_date
   v38.42.0: Fixes the bug where releasing items in React showed blank release_date
   even though the sheet had the correct value. Two interlocking problems:
   (1) handleReleaseItems_ never called SpreadsheetApp.flush() before returning,
   so the router's downstream api_fullClientSync_(clientSheetId, ["inventory"])
   call could re-open the sheet and read stale values (pre-write batched state).
   Evidence: Supabase audit showed the test tenant's inventory had updated_at
   frozen at yesterday's Bulk Sync timestamp despite multiple release actions
   being performed today — the sync HAD been running but reading stale data.
   (2) The router used the heavy api_fullClientSync_(... ["inventory"]) which
   re-reads the entire Inventory sheet and upserts every row — wasteful for a
   1-5 item release, and any silent failure leaves the full sheet stale. Every
   other single-entity write handler uses api_writeThrough_(r, entityType,
   tenantId, entityId) which calls resyncEntityToSupabase_ to re-read and upsert
   only the changed rows. Fix: (a) added SpreadsheetApp.flush() at the end of
   handleReleaseItems_ matching the handleStartTask pattern. (b) switched the
   releaseItems router case from api_fullClientSync_ to api_writeThrough_ with
   the itemIds from the payload. No schema changes. No React changes.
   v38.41.0: Fixes the dashboard Repairs + Will Calls Created column always showing em-dashes.
   v38.41.0: Fixes the dashboard Repairs + Will Calls Created column always showing em-dashes.
   Root cause was layered: (1) Supabase mirror tables had no `created_date` column,
   (2) sbRepairRow_/sbWillCallRow_ didn't write the field, (3) React's
   fetchRepairsFromSupabase/fetchWillCallsFromSupabase hardcoded createdDate: ''.
   Since the dashboard reads Supabase-first on mount, the empty string won every time.
   Fix: additive migration added `created_date text` to both mirror tables (no reordering,
   no drop), updated both row builders to write the field, and updated the React Supabase
   read path to map it. Existing rows need a one-time backfill via Settings → Maintenance
   → Bulk Sync to Supabase. Tasks are unaffected — they already had this wired end-to-end.
   v38.40.0: Closes the loop on the v38.37.0 setCol_ auto-create bug. v38.38.0 and v38.39.0
   fixed the Client Shipment Note symptom (title case on that one line, uppercase-normalized
   read path). This version makes the fix REUSABLE — every remaining setCol_ caller in
   api_updateClientRow_ now passes the canonical sheet case from api_clientRowToPayload_
   (Title Case throughout, except QB_CUSTOMER_NAME which stays ALL_CAPS for QuickBooks
   compatibility). So if any future client sheet is missing a column and setCol_'s
   auto-create branch fires, the new header is written with the correct convention,
   not accidentally mis-cased. setCol_'s internal lookup is still case-insensitive, so
   changing the callers' case is zero-risk — existing mis-cased columns still resolve.
   Also hardened api_ensureColumn_ (the other auto-create site, used by transfer/storage
   billing for the Transfer Date column): was case-sensitive and could create duplicate
   columns on case-drifted sheets; now does case-insensitive match with duplicate guard.
   Added a prominent CONVENTION comment block at the top of setCol_ documenting the
   Title Case rule for future contributors.
   v38.39.0: Cleaner fix for the v38.37.0 read-path case mismatch. Instead of spot-patching
   the Client Shipment Note lookup with an uppercase fallback (which leaves the same class
   of bug latent in every other obj[...] lookup), handleGetClients_ now builds its per-row
   obj with uppercase-normalized keys — matching the convention already used by
   api_clientRowToPayload_ and api_updateClientRow_. Every field extraction uses the
   uppercase variant, so column-case drift (sheet renames, setCol_ auto-create quirks,
   mixed-case duplicates) is structurally impossible to regress on. Removes the
   dual-lookup shipmentNote fallback added in v38.38.0 — no longer needed.
   v38.38.0: Fixes Session 53 save-doesn't-persist bug. Root cause: api_updateClientRow_'s
   setCol_ helper creates missing columns using the EXACT case of the passed colName. Prior
   code called setCol_("CLIENT SHIPMENT NOTE", ...) so the auto-created header was all-caps,
   but handleGetClients_ read it back with obj["Client Shipment Note"] (title case) — a
   case-sensitive JS object lookup that returned undefined. Data WAS being written to the
   sheet, just under the wrong-cased header. Fix: (1) pass title-case "Client Shipment Note"
   to setCol_ so future auto-creates use the sheet convention; setCol_'s internal lookup is
   already case-insensitive via toUpperCase(), so it still finds existing mis-cased columns.
   (2) handleGetClients_ adds a fallback to the uppercase variant so any column already
   created with the buggy case still reads correctly. This is the first time setCol_'s
   auto-create branch has fired in production — every other column is pre-created by
   onboarding, so the latent bug never surfaced before.
   v38.37.0: Adds CLIENT_SHIPMENT_NOTE — a per-client receiving instruction that surfaces as
   a prominent amber banner on the React Receiving page when the user selects that client.
   Use case: clients with strict receiving requirements (e.g. "open all boxes with driver
   present") that warehouse staff must see every time. Non-breaking — column auto-creates
   on first save via api_updateClientRow_'s built-in column creator, and getClients reads
   it by header name so missing columns are silently skipped. Settings-tab write is
   conditional (only when non-empty) to match qbCustomerName/staxCustomerId convention.
